Some of our members lately have been complaining that our company provided shoes are “Uncomfortable, awkward, and hideous.” As the designer of said shoes, I had to firmly disagree. And so, if you find anyone who has traded their pointy narrow yellow and green neon heels out for something less stylish, please let me know. I’ve noticed that everyone wearing them almost immediately trips onto their faces when springing from a bush, so if you encounter an ambush that trails you for longer, then you know you’ve found a filthy shoe swapper.

Even while being chased, you’d noticed the last guy was missing those garish shoes, though he still fell on his face at the end\..\..\.. In any case, how are you supposed to report him to his boss? What do you say? Some guy in a bush wasn’t wearing the shoes? Well, those shoes \fiare\fi atrocious, so you’ll just let this one slide.

\C[25]\fiI’ve tried to make the enemies more challenging in this dungeon, but as a result it’s possible the difficulty will be frustrating and require you to go back and grind enemies to be able to fight in this dungeon, which I want to avoid if at all possible. For that reason, you’ll now have two difficulty downs in your inventory, which when used will increase your power and defense by five. I hope you’ll try fighting the enemies without using them first, but if you are struggling then these will help without requiring you to spend time fighting old enemies over and over. Also, if you find you are too strong and want more of a challenge, you have two difficulty ups as well, which will lower your power and defense by five. Each time you adjust the difficulty, you’ll get the opposite item, so if you use both difficulty ups, you’ll have four difficulty downs, so you can always undo the changes if you’d like.
